subSubSection.paragraph:
Habitat.
The Chowsingha is a habitat generalist but prefers dry deciduous mixed forest with thickets of trees and shrubs (even within open dry patches), hilly terrain, and areas of limited human disturbance. It avoids disturbed areas but tends to use other habitats in proportion to their availabilities. High, grassy vegetation is frequently used and provides protection from predators, which include Tigers (Panthera 
tigris
), Leopards (P. pardus), and Dholes (Cuon 
alpinus
); the Chowsingha rarely exceeds 15% of any of those predator’s diets. Despite occupying dry forests, local distributions of Chowsinghas are constrained by daily need for free water.
